{"/service/ndnp/wvu/batch_wvu_jim_ver01/data/sn86092536/00271767961/1920122901/0072.xml":{"full_text":"emicer\n\"published by The Intelligencer PuDllehlng Company.\nTELEPHONES\nEditorial Rooms No. 823 Business Office No. 822\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRKSS.\nTne Associated Press la ficluilwly entitled to the use for republication of\nI) news credited to It or not otherwise credited ui this paper, and also the local\nnews published herein. All rights of republication of special dispatches hereto\nare also reserved\n(THE INTELLIGENCER, embracing Its several editions, Is entered In the\nPostofflce ?t 'Wheeling, W. Va.. aa second dan mall matter.)\nCosnplasnta of non-delivery of The Intslltgsncer will be adjusted by calling\nTtsr Boyd Circulation Manager. Phone >11 or IH.\nI AOC^^^lw^lCIL\nWe^esday, December 29, 1920.\norii 'pacific1 allies\nThat Canada. Australia. New Zealand and South Africa may Join with the\nHatted States in presenting a united front on the subject of Japanese Immigra-j\ntion is an Interesting possibility. Negotiation* with that object In view are now\nIn prepress and each of the countries mentioned has expressed its recognition of I\nthe Identical Interests of all Ave.\nIt Is a rather fortunate circumstance that there should l>e such a com\nmunity of Interest between ourselves and all of the four big self-governing\ndominions of Great Prltaln. Our own attitude on the subject of Oriental lmml-,\ngratlon would be the same anyhow, but It Is pelasing to be aide to point t-> thej\nfact that other countries take the name stand.\nIn all matters Involving Asiatic race questions, our Interests In the I'aciflc J\nwill always be the ?ame as those of the British dominions. An alliance, or even'\nformal understanding is not absolutely necessary in such a case, for identity of J\ninterest better than either when the actual test comes. This was demon-.\nI\nI rated vividly at the beginning of the w?rM war. when Italy renounced her\nallegiance to the triple alliance composed of Germany. Austria and herself.\nNo diplomatic maneuvering is necessary to align Canada. Australia. New;\nZealand. South Africa and the United States. This dies not mean that these!\ncountries contemplate a clash with Japan over the subject of Immigration, but\nit does mean that the.r combined attitude will be of such an Impressive nature\nthat unpleasant developments which might otherwise result, may be avoided.\nJustice should prevail In lite settlement of the Japanese Immigration uu*'s- j\ntion. but there are certain points that cannot be conceded. Necessary loglsla-|\nt'.on should be so framed as not to hurt the feelings of Japanese or other:\nOriental races unnecessarily* hut the main object must be attained.\ni\nINSTRUCTIONS FROM\nMOSCOW\"\nFir .?onse time, the United States gov\nernment has been considering the de\nportation of Ludwlg C. A. K. Martens.,\nthe Bolshevist \"Ambassador\" to this\ncountry. In this connection, there ap\npeared In Tuesday's papers, a rather\npeculiar paragraph. *s follows:\nNew York. Dec. ?7. I.udwlg A. K.\nMartens. Russian Soviet \"ambassador\"\nto the United States, today notified the\nliepartment of labor that upon Instruc\ntions from the Moscow *overnment Just\njecelved cable, he will surrender hlnr\ns?lf for deportation January 3.\nJu??t what connection the Moscow\ngovernment has with the case of Mr.\nMartens Is not clear. Since when has\nour department of labor been taking in\nMructlons from Lenlne and Trot ikv as\nto the deportation of undesirable citi\nzens? The Impression convoyed by th>>\nmessage of Martens Js that his deporta\ntion of undesirable citizens? The Im\npression conveyed by the message of\nMartens Is that his deportation de\npended upon his Instructions from Mos\ncow and he even goes so far as to fix\nthe date on which he will consent to let\nUncle Sam get rid of him It should\nt be made plain to Martens and to Mos\ncow that the United States will deport\nor not as It see* fit. without any \"In\nstruc'lor.s\" or advice from abroad, and\n'particularly from the Soviet govern\nmen-t.\nCANAL TO BE PROTECTED\n1 Proper protection of the Panama\n'canal apparently la to be an early ro\n'sult of the recent visit of President\nelect Hardin* to the canal lone. Uv\nthe provisions of a measure soon to be\n.presented to the house of representa\ntives .the canal would be made virtually\nImpregnable. This Is exactly the way\nthe American people want it to be, and\n'as the cost will not be great. there Is no\nreason why the proposed fortifications\nshould not be Installed In tne near\nfuture.\nAt the present time, the artillery de\nfending the canal is too small. The\n^largest of modern battleships carry\nguns that would enable them to remain\n'out of ranpe and destroy the- Mlraflore\nlocks. The existing fortification* were\n.built without regard to attack from the\n,?tr and consequently are fully exposed\nto such attacks.\n4 In conpection with the new plans, it Is\nInteresting: to note that the railroad\ntrack system of artillery is to be ueetl\n<>n the Atlantic side. By thla system,\nbig jruns are mounted on specially de\nsigned cars and ruahed from place to\nplace as they may be needed, concrete\nplatforms to reinforce the cars being\nprovided at certain intervals. During\nthe world war. this system was used In\na somewhat primitive way by the Turks\nand Germans In defending the Darda\nnelles and proved very effective. Later,\nit was used to some extent on the\nwestern front. It has been advocated\nfor our eeacoasts. and if the Panama\nexperiment should prove its practicabil\nity. a general system of such coast de\nfenses would be a probable develop\nment.\nDANGER SIGNALS\nIn the reorganisation of tho comtnit\nof union labor m?n to organize the\nsteel Industry, neither John Fltzpatrick\nnor W. Z. Foster wts ?lected to an of\nficial position. These two m^n. It will\nbe recalled. led the *trllce last year,\n?which was marked by radicalism, It 1*\nstated that the conservative element has\npermitted the Impression to go out that\nFoster and Fltzpatrick have been prac\nticAlly eliminated from the organlza\ntioa on account of their radicalism The\ntvfo former leaders and their friends ara\nsaid to resent this Implication.\nIf the steel workers expect to create\npublic confidence, they must do more\nthan merely permit an \"lmpressfon\" to\nko out that Foster and Fltzpatrick have\nbeen repudiated. So strong Is the feel\ning of all the better elemeftts of Amer\nica against radicalism that any assocla\nilon which continues to harbor such\nmen as Foster and Fltzpatrick will be\nunder constant suspicion. In the re\ncent election, all brands of radicalism\nwere hopelessly \"snowed under.\" That\nwas a correct expression of national\nsentiment which all organisations would\nrio well to heed. The public Is willing\nand even ea^r to cooperate with sane\nand conservative movements for the ad\nvancement of the workinsman. but It,\nlooks upon the \"red\" element In exactly\nth.j same way that the engineer of a\npassenger train looks at a red liicht.\nNOT THE PROPER TIME\nThat tha passage of soldier bonne\nlegislation at tha present time would be\ndlractly oppoaad to th? best interests\nof tha nation and would prevanr tha\nearly stabilisation of American finance\nand Industry Is the position of Secre\ntary of the Treasury Houston. He es-j\n4\ntlmates that such legislation would coat\nj J3.3OO.OOO.OO0. This enormous Bum\nwautd jro, not to benefit the nation as a\ni whole through some plan to revive i\nj trade and Industry, but to Individuals.'\nI I* would bo a direct drain on the tress-\nury. with no return, and would make a!!\nefforts to reduce the present burdens of\n1 taxation absolutely hopeless,\nj Stabilisation of finance and Industry!\nis our one great national need right now. i\nJust as soon an costs have reached a!\ncondition of undoubted stability, confl\ndence will return, business will be ro\nj ?um?d with i?. rush and Industry will\nquickly follow. Kvery big national ex\npenditure will interfere with atablllza\nj tlon by disturbing credit and renewing\nthe infliction of prices.\nKormer service men do not want to\n'delay the return of prosperity any'\n'mora than anybody else. The limit of j\nthe bonus to one Individual would be\n1500, which would not compensate even\ntbosc fortunate enough to get it f-->r a j\nperiod of hard times. The nation Is fac\nIng big and difficult problems and\nshould be able to count on the assist- 1\nance of Legion men to solve them. The i\nsooner the country gets on its financial\nand Industrial feet, the sooner it will b?- 1\nin a position to give the service men\nI what they *?nt.\nWHY WE HAVE LYNCHINGS\nI Lynching will conttnue to be oru? of j\nthe blots on our national escutcheon\nJust as Ion* as men charged with the)\nI investigation of these crimes take such\naction us that of the grand jury at Fort\nWorth. Texas. This body of represent-!\native cltisens, assembled to probe a\nlynching than took place !a.?t Wednes- j\nday night, informed the court that It;\nhad \"neither un indictment nor a re- 1\nport to make.\" and requested to be e\\-\ni cused.\nIn other words, this grand jury was.\nso cowardly and so lacking in a sense of!\npublic responsibility that It did not even\ndare to make a report on Its investiga-j\ntton. The obvious inference Is that the\nJurors knew the lynchers but did not J\n1 care to Indict them nor to do anything\nthat might lead to their arrest.\nIt is perfectly safe to predict that j\nthere will be more lynchlngs In the Tort\nWorth vicinity. When the knowledge of\nImmunity from punishment Is added to\nthe desire to take criminals out of the j\nbands of the law. lynchlngs follow a* j\ninevitably as darkness follows daylight, j\ni Because h? carried a turk'-y with Us\nj head down, a New York Good Samaritan i\nj was arrested by a liurclano agent and\nspent Christmas in Jail, while the poor!\nfamily to which he was taking the;\nturkey had no Christmas dinner. The j\n'Judge who heard the case whs angry,'\nbut not at the prisoner. Even humane i\nagents make mistakes sometimes.\ni The new play dramatized from the\nfamous novel, \"Miss Lulu Bett\" was!\ntried out on the Sing Sing convicts be- j\ni fore being presented In New York. I\nThis should call forth a vigorous pro- 1\ntest. A man has a right to some <>on- 1\nslderatlon. even when In Jail.\ni We venture a guess that General\nPershing will lead Harding's Inaugural\nparado with greater personal enthusiasm j\nthan he would have led that of Mr.\nCo*.\nTil? coffin of Attlla the Hun has been\nfound In the bed of the Aranka river\nj In Hungary. It would be Interesting to\nlook and see whether he turned tn his\ngrave when Kaiser Bill rot busy.\nA New Yorker claims to have dls\n1 covered a blue lobster. They'll all be i\nI that color If those Puritan Sunday laws j\ngo through.\nj Funds for tha atarYlng children of\nEurope are coming In slowly. The chil\ndren are dying the same way.\nThat report about D'Annunzlo's duath I\nI waa exaggerated. He's only dead from\nj the neck up.\nj Ptttaburgh's hills and street cars do\nnot seem to get along well together.\n[HOW THEY STOPPED\nSHOE PROFITEERING\nllilbao. 8t>atn. Pec. 28 The mere an\nnouncement by a shoe dealer hare that\nJ he had made a contract with an Amerl\ncan firm to send SS.^'tO pairs of shoes\nto Bilbao on trial, with a view to fur\nther orders. produced a panic among the\natore-keepars of thU city. The an\nnouncement stated the American shoes\nwould he sold at half the pre'.alllng\nprice of the home-made article*. Imm#\ni diately afterward prices came rtown with\na run.\ni The loca! newspapers, \\dvlse other\nlocalities to follow the '.on of 'lie north\nern city and thus pn? .1 *t?p U> profi\nteerlng\ni\nCOLONEL HOUSE\nDiscusses Armaments and Their Effect on National\nPolicy Cause of the\nWorld War.\nBy COL^E? M. HOUSE\nCopyright, 1?;\", by Wh^'Hn* Intelligcnccr ?nd Public I.edger comi?ry.\nNew York, Pec. CS. The question of a general reduction of armaments is\nat t>i<* moment one that Is uppermost in the public mind.\nEducation should play a lar<e part in I lie eradication of war. There is a\nfull realization when \\?ar is in progress of th* suffering and hardship which it\nentails, bui this realization becomes dim very soon In times of peace. It Is\na merciful provision of Providence that our affliclioitH may bo forgotten, but\nunhappily the horrors of war also art? softened ns the years go by. A better\nreminder is the tax we have to pay day by day and the effort which must be\nniadn to nteet it. This burden goes on from one generation to another.\nYouth in particular, und people In general, should be constantly reminded\ntliat wars, past, present and prospective, nru laying a daily tribute upon their\nenergies und resources. They should be taught that they arc denied many com\nforts and conveniences because of war arid the threat of it How many realise\nthat for e\\ery dollar paid for taxes. S!> or I'O percent is for this wasteful\npurpose?\nGeneral Tasker H. Bliss' masterly exposition at the Philadelphia Academy\nof Music forum upon the question of disarmament, and Senator Borah's resolu\ntion In the Senate upon the same subject are creating wide Interest. The ques\ntion is, as General Bliss says, the essence of the program for peace.\nArmament Bac* Caused War.\nIl wns the race in armaments a* much as anything else wnicn precipuaiec.1\nthe world war. It was not only military but na\\al armaments as well which\ncaused' the mischief. When Great Hrltaln began to build an entirely new type\nof battleship a type so different and so much more powerful than any other\nthen in existence the effect was to practically .scrap every navy in the world\nand make It necesrr.ry to begin anew. Germany paw her opportunity and began\nas quickly as possible to build dreadnoughts and later super-dreadnoughts.\nKxcept for the !a<*k of building plants she was practically on an oven basis with\nGreat Britain, whose superiority vanished when th? tlrst dreadnought was\nlaunched.\nThose were feverish days In naval circles, not only in Kngland hut else\nwhere. The British discovered, or thought they bad. that the Geramns were\nbuilding against them alone, and in evidence of this It was said that th? new\nGerman construction provided coaling spaco for short cruises only. With th\nlargest military force In the world, and with u navy equal to Great Britain's.\nGermany's proximity to l?ngland constituted a menace not to be ignored.\nIf German statesmanship had equaled German efficiency, the mistake would\nnot have been made in thinking that in a war involving the centra! powers with\nFrance and Russia, Great Britain would remain neutral. While Franc* and\nRussia had been England's traditional enemies and Germany had been her tra\nditional friend, the avowed Intention of Germany to build n navy equal to that\nof any other power, made certain Great Britain's entrance against her.\nWaral Powir P>t*rminlng T actor.\nThe statement that naval power Is not also a menace to the general pcace.\nand that It cannot endanger the liberties of nny country is not tenable, Sea\npower, as Admiral Maban has pointed out. Is usually the determining factor In\nwar. It has proven lts?lf so in many instances from Salamis to the present\nday. Therefore, in any discussion of a reduction of armaments, the mtval sido\nassumes as much Importance as the military.\nWhen a nation's Intentions are questioned, either en land or en sea. the\nanswer Is always that the armaments planned are for salf-protectlon only.\nGermany stated this repeatedly before the war, and maintained that her navy\nwas only for the purpose of coping with the na\\ies of France and Russia In the\nevent of war. and of protecting her growing commerce. The same assertion is\nbeing mad* today by Great Britain. Japan and the I'nited States as to their\nnavies, and by France. Russia and othor Eurppcn countries regarding their\narmlaa.\nAt i'arla. when Lloyd Gorge first suggested that not only should the Ger\nman army bo reduced to l'.?0.000 men, but even that small number sholud be\nraised by the volunteer system, a body blow war struck at German militarism.\nTo those who knew in advance that such a proposal would be made. It was\nthought that France and Italy might object for tlic reason that if Germany\nli\\ed and thrived under such conditions, there would be an Insistent demand:\nfrom their own people for a discontinuance of conscription. However, no objec- j\ntlon was made and the proposal became a part of the peace terms.\nHope la \"Kara! Holiday.\"\nIt has been contended that Great Britain and the United States were the\nonly two nations rich enough to raise armies by the volunteer method, because\nthey were the only ones able to pay an amount sufficient to attract enlistment.\nThe surest and most direct road to general disarmament, both en land and\non s?.-a. !s through the League of Nations; but since that at the moment cannot\nbe. It is to be hoped that a beginning may be made by the United Stales agree- j\nIng to a naval holiday for a period of at least five years.\nEvery suggestion made at (ieneva looking inward disarmament was met\n\nby a reference to the United States and our attitude was given as an excuse,\nfor their want of action. This Is an intolerable position for any nation to\noccupy following Buch a hitman cataclysm as thai of the world war. and it is\nto be hoped that Senator Borah's resolution may be adopted and subsequently j\nfollowed by negotiations that will Indicate that peace, justice and good fellow- j\nship among men are the underlying principles of this mighty republic.\nTerrible Conditions Are J\nRevealed In Near East\nBy Relief Workers1\n\\>w York. Deo. 18. Tli r?*o thousand\nArmenians, driven from their homes in1\ntho war-ravaged countries south of the\nBlack Sea. are concentrated in old\nchurches or other refugee building in\nConstantinople, says a report recolvod\nhere by the Near Kant Relief from on?\nof lt? workers). Their fate fs described\nas wretched Work la at a premium In\nConstantinople because of the Influx of\n100,000 Russian refugees from thn\nCriemo* and numerous lireeks from tho\nfighting zone In Anatolia.\nThe buildings in which the Armenian\nrefugees have been herded are charac- j\nterlzed as unsuitable In almost every\nconceivable way for housing ho many.\nThere are Ave o fthese refugee centers.\ncalled camps.\nThe relief worker reports that sanl-j\nUrv conditions In these camps are al- 1\nmost Indescribable. Tho buildings am j\ncrowded, dirty and wet. The refugees,\nmost of them country people unuuued to I\nthe ways of the city and stupefied by j\ntheir misfortunes, sit around huddled\nagainst the walls Tho women have\ndull, sad faces, and the little children\nar? blue and pinched with the cold and\ntoo miserably lifeless to cry.\nTho women make an effort to keep j\nclean, but It Is hard to wash either\nbodies or clothes when th?re Is no\nsoap, about one pan or kettle for ten\nfamilies, and all the water from one\nwe!!.\nMost of the refupees have arrived In\nConstantinople with almost nothing ex\ncept the clothes on their backs, and\nmany are barely covered.\nKven greater need exists for blankets\nthan warm clothing. One family of five,\nfor Instance, sleeps on a bare stone\nfloor under one thin, ragged, half cotton\nblanket.\nAt Hankeuy camp, located In an old\nArmenian church, 6>0 persons from\nCllicla are housed. 250 of them women\nand children. They are hungry most of\nthe tlino Every two days tlm c?mi> r?\ncwlvns 1 SO loaves of bread and one case\nof milk from the Central Armenian com\nmittee. The milk Is reserved for the\nbabies and the sick. They cook over\ntwig fires and with the constant rain\nand mud. dry twigs are hard to find.\nI'samatlu. a \"special feeding camp\"\nwhere the wenkent refugees are sent,\nhas H50 people, and conditions are\nslightly better Scutari, another \"spe\ncial\" camp for sick refugoe*. consists of\ntwo old churches In which 36a peoplo\nare massed.\nAt Bechlktache camp, n large Turkish j\nhouse, formerly occupied by u Pasha,\nsnd his harem. 4S1 miserable Armenians,\ndwell. They are given nothing but the\nroof over their liuads. Some of thein\nhave a little money which they spend In\nthe tmlcst InstallnientB for rice or!\nI bread Ortnkeuv camp. located In two\nbulldltiKs. one a delaptdnted palace, and\nthe other left in a tilth)* condition by\nTurkish troops, houses 730.\nMAT ViXZ LOKD WSLLITTOTO W J\nj Slrnln, Pec. 2?. (India Information\nBureau) Several names for tn? Vice-\nroyalty of India have been proposed,\nrecently, besides WtaHton Churchill, war\nminister of England. Mary view It as i\nIncreasingly probable that Hit appoint- I\nniont will go to Lord Welllngdon. t'no\n1 present governor of Madras.\nLord Wllllngrdon has been governor of\ntwo Indian provinces. Madras and Bom\nbay. For n time he narvod an Junior lord\nof the treasury un ter Sir Henry Camp-\nball Uannerman.\ni JLEBZAL DEEBY raOPOSEP.\nI furls. l>ec. C4. The Aviation ComiulR-\nI sion of the French Aero l'Iuh has ap-\n'pointed a sub-oommlsalon for the pur- j\nj pose of studying the arrangements tot\nan aerial derby around the world, in I\nagreement with the rapresenUtlvoa In'\n1 Paris of the \\merlcau promoters of i\nthat project.\nI\nBunion Shoes\nFor Men j\nAre you troubled with an enlarge- j\nment of the joint or a bunion? j\nWe have a Shoe specially built to|\novercome being troubled with a\nj new shoe at this particular\npoint. Made of verv soft leath-'\ni t\ner, also an enlarged place in the\nshoe for the joint to rest with\ni ease. \"No breaking in.\" Small\nin I he heel to overcome the foot\nworking forward. Best of work\ninanship, nothing left out that\nwould increase your comfort. j\n$11.00\n\nM. H. M.\nSatisfactory Shoes\n1047 Main St. Wheeling\nNo Prettier Dresses\nArc to be had, even if you -were to pay much more thun our rcgularly-markcd prices for\nthem. Now you have choice of the entire collection\nStreet, Afternoon and Evening Dresses g\nWool, Silk, Charmeuse, Tricolette Dresses\nMisses', Average and Stylish Stout Dresses\nDivided Into Three 1/ 1 1 1/\nSpecial Assortments /a Qflfl /n\nWith Prices Reduced /O\nSecond-Day Selection is sure to Satisfy your Dress Needs.\nUMBRELLAS FOE WOMEN? O\nWith $3.39 Values Belling at fc* I VJ\nThis new lot of Cfiristmas Umbrellas arrived \"the day after.\" That's the reason for\nthe sensational saving on\nFast-Black, Tape-edge Umbrellas for Men and Women.\nFor Ladies, with Ring or Loop Handles.\nFor Men with Mission or Crook Handles. A Q\nSplendid Umbrellas for $3.89, Wednesday special at..\nFinest Black and Colored Silk Umbrellas iL\nEnter the After-Christmas Sale today LESS V-rDG? JL OUriO\nNow's the Time to Buy\nTOYS, DOLLS, GAMES, ETC.\nAt After-Christmas Savings o\nTwo Wednesday Basement Bargains\ni\n\"THERMOS\" LUNCH KITS\nBlack enamel metal Lunch Kits fitted with\nPint -size \"Thermos\" hot-or-cold bottle, in\nstead of $4.73, Wednesday\nat\n$3.98\nCHOCOLATE BETH\nCovered Pot, six Cups and six Saucers of .j\nhand-painted Nippon China, in three pretty\ndecorations. $5.75 fourteen\npiece Sets, special (jjO* f.Uf- 1*!\nI Buy Any of Our Silk 1/\nat Savings of One-Fourth /4\nOn many Special Lines, the\nI savings range up to about /2\nPreviously Advertised I\nClearances!\nContinued\n\nGeo. M. Snook Co.\nWASHINGTON\nWest Virgin!* Newi Notea\nand Gossip at the Natian'n\nCapital\nWashington, L>. I IS.-- Walter\nCunningham, of Huntington, aocretarj\nof t lie West Virginia <'\"*1 Operators' j\nAssociation, Is In the cl'.y on business i\nconnected with the coal trade.\nJo! in S. Miller, of Webster Spring*, I\nis u visitor in th?s city.\nSenator f? u t her lit nrl <>n Monday took j\nup with the pension commissioner, urg- 1\nlug ImmcdliTte decision. the application\nof Mr*. Marlon Filler, of Waynes-.\nLurg, l'a and Carl C. l'unham, of Wes- 1\nton. W. Va.\nFred W. Perkins, head of the educa-\nHon film department of the Department I\n?>f Agriculture, wan summoned to Illn- 1\nion, W. \\'a., Christmas evening by a\ntelegram announcing the death of a\nAMERICANS ABANDON\nGERMAN TRADE FIELD\ni\nHerlln, Dec. 28. American business1\nscouts who have been scouring Germany,\nin the last few months In search of\ncontracts have virtually nhandoned th?j\nli?id to the ISritish and French and\n8'>n? home, according to Information\nreaching the American Association of\nCommerce and Trade here. While ex\nports nnd imports between the I'nlted\nStates nnd Germany continue gradual\nly t'< lncreuse. the Americans say the\nMinority of the big manufacturing and\nbuying firms of Germany already have\nsigned long-time cov tracts with the\nBritish and French, who sent armies\nof representatives Into the# country as\nsoon as the armistice was signed.\nThe (iennftns who have not contract\ned with the British and French. but|\nhave held back In the belief that it\nwould be to their advantage to tie up\nw i tli the Americans, are becoming dis\ncouraged, and American business men,\nhere say unless there is soon a resump\nI ion of official relations between the\ntwo countries, and probably a stabiliza\nlion of exchange. It must be many!\nmonths after a treaty Is signed betoro\nthe Americans will again have their)\nproportionate pre-war share of German\"\nradi*\nThe German government is keenly!\nn 1 i\\ to the situation, and even harxj\ntaken n hand unofficially In reccnfcj\ntransactions l>y which It was believed j\ngood business rein t ions between the two!\ncountries would be festered. When' the\nNational Cash Register company re\ncently sought permlKSlon of the politi\ncal economic suh-committeo of the Im\nperial economic council to Import\ntools nnd patterns for a factory !n Ger-j\ntnHny, th<> Merman foreign office took j\nan active interest, anil It Is said avenj\ndirected t h?? committor to make a favor- j\nable report, although some of Ger\nmany's most powerful financial influ\nences were objecting.\nOther American concerns have ap\nplied for permission to Import ma\nchinery and manufactured articles, but\nthe economic council has thus far wlth-(\nh?*ld the permission on the ground the\narticles could bo produced In Germany.!\nThe German government's principal;\nehectlon to Importations at this tint*.\nIs bused upon the low exchange value\nof the mark. Until the mark Is stabi\nlized. the Germans believe trade should j\nb? encouraged on the basis of exchange'\nof goods, or that only such Imports- j\nti'?ns should ba permitted as will en-j\neournge German production and form'\na market for German labor.\nWo Sunday Vapart or Bars.\nIn Malhourno no Sunday papers are\npermitted and no hotels are ailoned\nt<> open their bats.\nTHE COAL SHORTAGE\nTo What Extent Labor and Futile Strikes Are\nResponsible.\nBy HARRY A. WHEELER\nFormer President of the Chamber of Commerce of the IT. S. f\nThere in a shortage !n tho coal sup\nply of the world and thin shortage la\nfelt with considerable force In the\nI'nlted 8tates generally.\nA great many statement* that have\nbeen made concerning the situation\nhave been speculative and have behind\nthem just enough of the truth to war\nrant the exercise of Imagination with\nreaped to the seriousness of conditions\nand this dangers with which wo are con\nfronted.\nInevitably an effort has been made to\nfasten responsibility, both for the pres\nent shortage and the present high\nprices. A v*st number of remedies\nhave been suggested, some of which are\nsound and man? of which are impossi\nble of accomplishment under the com\nplex conditions which now obtain in\nproduction and in transportation.\nOne lesson has been taught un by\nthe war, namely, thai the common\ncommodities of daily life become su\npreme commodities in time* of crisis\nand in every national or international\nemergency. When conditions are nor\nmal we think very little of these com\nmodities. Our coal supply we take as\na matter of course.